  "texts": [
    "Since h p (x)R ′ i y ′, we have y ′ ⊑ ′ f ′ i (h p (x)) by Lemma 5.15, so y ′ ⊑ ′ h p (f i (x)) by (e).",
    "Then since h p (f i (x)) ⊑ h p (f i (x) ∧ h(y ′)) by (a), we have that y ′ ⊑ h p (f i (x) ∧ h(y ′)).",
    "Third, we have h p (f i (x) ∧ h(y ′)) ⊑ y ′ by (d).",
    "Thus, we have shown that h p (f i (x) ∧ h(y ′)) = y ′, so setting y = f i (x) ∧ h(y ′) completes the proof of p-R-back.For part 2, assuming h is surjective, we must show that (i) h p (y) ⊑ ′ h p (x) implies y ⊑ x (so h is injective), (ii) h p (x)R ′ i h p (y) implies xR i y, and (iii) for all X ∈ P there is anX ′ ∈ P ′ such that h p [X] = h p [S] ∩ X ′, where S is the domain of A p. For (i), if h p (y) ⊑ ′ h p (x), then ′ {y ′ ∈ A ′ | y ≤ h(y ′)} ≤ ′ ′ {x ′ ∈ A ′ | x ≤ h(x ′)} by definition of h p and ⊑ ′ ⇒ h( ′ {y ′ ∈ A ′ | y ≤ h(y ′)}) ≤ h( ′ {x ′ ∈ A ′ | x ≤ h(x ′)}) since h is a homomorphism ⇒ {h(y ′) | y ≤ h(y ′)} ≤ {h(x ′) | x ≤ h(x ′)} since h is complete ⇒ y ≤ xsince h is surjective, so y ⊑ x since y ∈ A p. For (ii), if h p (x)R ′ i h p (y), then by Lemma 5.15,h p (y) ⊑ ′ f ′ i (h p (x)), which with (e) implies h p (y) ⊑ ′ h p (f i (x)), which with (i) implies y ⊑ f i (x), which with Lemma 5.15 implies xR i y.",
    "Finally, for (iii), suppose X ∈ P, so by Definition 5.14.5, either X = ∅ or X = ↓x for some non-minimum element x of A."
